## What I learned
- Pointers -> & means get the address (what is the address???)
			  * means it goes to that address (go to that address!!!)
- * is also called dereferencing

	For ex: int n = 50;
		int *p = &n;
		printf("%i", *p); -> 50
	
	In above code, I was thinking why did *p not pass &n (i.e. address of n) instead of the actual n value - because that's what was done in previous line.
  
  	In fact, the 2nd line tells the compiler that *p is a pointer variable which points to an address. So when *p is printed, compiler knows that * is mentioned which means dereference n and give the value of it.
  	Remember: If a variable is declared with * -> means it is a pointer variable
	But anywhere else *p -> means dereference p or go to that address that p holds and get value.

- Memory management: 
	1. SMA - Static memory allocation: all declared variables (uninitialized local variables and initialized variables). Will be present at compile time. Goes to stack.
	2. DMA - Dynamic memory allocation: variables declared during run time (uses malloc, calloc, realloc and free). Goes to Heap.
	3. Data segment - global declared variables
	4. bss - undeclared global variables

- Don't forget to use free() or it will do memory leak: It means that when you initialize a variable using malloc (for ex. p), the initialized variable is in stack. But it points to the dynamically allocated variable in heap. If you don't use heap, stack will destroy the value p but the memory in heap is still there and cannot be consumed so it gets wasted. 

- Use %p for addresses.

- sizeof operator is of type size_t which is unsigned. Use %zu to get value.

- (1 << 7) - directly means that I am moving 1 to 7th bit (assumes that 1 is already at 0th bit and then move 7 times left) and rest all are 0 (bits 0-6).

- If you compare below, the compiler converts to specific types:
	signed  vs unsigned  →  signed gets converted to unsigned
	smaller type vs bigger type  →  smaller gets converted to bigger

- Type casting: For ex: 
	int a = 5;
    int b = 2;
    float result1 = a / b; //a/b will be done as an integer and then the result will be converted to float. Therefore, 5/2 = 2.
    float result2 = (float)a / b; //a and b will act as float here while dividing. Therefore, 5/2 = 2.5

- Use suffix to define type. For ex. f for float, u for unsigned, l for long, etc.
	Usage: 3.3f, 3u, 3l

- Logical operator vs bitwise operator:
	int p = 5;   // 0101
    int q = 3;   // 0011
    printf("p && q = %d\n", p && q);  // 1; logical operator: (is q true?) AND (q is true?). True means 1 or greater than 1.
    printf("p & q  = %d\n", p & q);  // 1; bitwise operator: bit by bit operation.
    printf("p || q = %d\n", p || q); // 1; (is p true?) OR (is q true?)

- When we do i++, that means the value of i itself changes, i = i+1.

- If you compare a signed vs unsigned, compiler converts it to unsigned...therefore in below code:
	int8_t a = -1; //11111111 - represented as 2's compliment in compiler (flip all bits thn add 1)
	uint8_t b = 1; //00000001
	if (a < b)
		printf("a is less than b\n"); //when a becomes unsigned, its 255 and b is 1, so this doesn't work.
	else
		printf("b is less than a\n"); //this gets printed


